It is worth mentioning the related works [22, 16], which focus on the minimization of the bending energy without constraints. In [6] we obtained equilibrium shapes by minimizing the membrane energy following a gradient flow. We consider in this paper a biomembrane model which incorporates the effect of the bulk fluid. The principal motivations are
• Obtain more faithful physical dynamics compared with the artificial gradient flow dynamics;
• Investigate how the presence of the fluid may affect the final equilibrium configuration, for example the equilibrium shapes achieved by the gradient flow might not be realistic due to possible membrane self-intersection. Moreover, it turns out that the inertia might lead to pinching not predicted by the geometric flow.
Numerical simulations are performed using parametric finite elements yielding a precise computation of curvatures. However, topological changes cannot be handled with the present method. We refer to the work of Du et al. [19] for a phase-field method on a similar system. The rest of the paper is organized as follows. We introduce notations in Section 2., which are employed in Sections 3. and 4.. They are devoted to the description of the geometric and fluid biomembrane models together with their corresponding numerical schemes. In Section 5., we present numerical simulations of both models and discuss their qualitative differences.
2. Notations
Let ω be a bounded domain of R3 with smooth boundary γ. We denote by x the identity on γ which can be seen as a parametrization of γ from a reference surface γˆ. In our dynamical(discrete) context, γˆ is taken to be either the initial surface or the surface at the previous time step. The outward unit normal of γ is denoted by ν. Let E be the canonical (along the normal direction [1]) extension operator from γ to a tubular neighborhood of γ. Let φ be C1 vector valued functions defined on γ. The tangential gradient of φ is defined to be the orthogonal projection of ∇E(φ) to the tangent hyperplane of γ
∇γφ := (I − ν ⊗ ν)∇E(φ)|γ.
This definition is independent of the extension since only depends on the tangential variation of E(φ)|γ = φ over γ. The tangential divergence of φ is defined by divγ φ := Trace(∇γφ). Finally, when φ is C2, the surface Laplacian or Laplace Beltrami operator is defined by ∆γφ := divγ (∇γφ).
We end this section by recalling the fundamental relation between the parametrization x of a surface γ and its vector total curvature h (sum of its principal curvatures in the normal direction)
h = −∆γx. (2.1)
This formula is classical in differential geometry and was first used by Dziuk [20] in the context of finite element methods for the mean curvature flow.
